2. Technical Architecture

2.1 System Overview

NEOS employs a layered architecture that separates concerns while maintaining tight integration where required for safety:

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                 APPLICATION LAYER                   │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Control Systems │  Safety Systems  │  Monitoring   │
│                  │                  │               │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│              SERVICE ABSTRACTION LAYER              │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│   Messaging   │   Database   │   Security   │  AI   │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                CORE OPERATING SYSTEM                │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Real-Time Kernel │ HAL │ Quantum Network │ Blockchain│
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

2.2 Real-Time Deterministic Kernel

Design Philosophy:

· Rate Monotonic Scheduling (RMS) for periodic tasks
· Earliest Deadline First (EDF) for aperiodic tasks
· Mixed-criticality support (MCS) for safety-critical functions
· CPU isolation and affinity for deterministic execution

Key Specifications:

· Scheduling Granularity: 100 microseconds
· Context Switch Time: <5 microseconds
· Maximum Jitter: <10 microseconds for safety tasks
· Interrupt Latency: <1 microsecond
· Memory Protection: Hardware-enforced isolation

Mathematical Foundation:

```
RMS Utilization Bound: U(n) = n(2^(1/n) - 1)
Where n = number of tasks

Response Time Analysis:
R_i = C_i + Σ_{j∈hp(i)} ⌈R_i/T_j⌉ C_j

Where:
R_i = Response time of task i
C_i = Worst-case execution time of task i
T_j = Period of higher-priority task j
hp(i) = Set of higher-priority tasks
```

2.3 Hardware Abstraction Layer (HAL)

Supported Hardware:

· FPGAs: Xilinx Ultrascale+, Intel Stratix 10 with radiation-hardened variants
· PLCs: Siemens S7-1500, Allen-Bradley ControlLogix, Schneider Electric Modicon
· Fieldbuses: Foundation Fieldbus H1/HSE, PROFIBUS DP/PA, HART
· Industrial Ethernet: EtherNet/IP, PROFINET, Modbus TCP
· Sensors: Radiation, temperature, pressure, flow, vibration (100+ types)

Memory-Mapped I/O Implementation:

```c
// Atomic read-modify-write for safety-critical registers
uint32_t atomic_rmw(volatile uint32_t* addr, uint32_t mask, uint32_t value) {
    uint32_t old_val, new_val;
    do {
        old_val = __atomic_load_n(addr, __ATOMIC_ACQUIRE);
        new_val = (old_val & ~mask) | (value & mask);
    } while (!__atomic_compare_exchange_n(addr, &old_val, new_val, 
                                          false, __ATOMIC_RELEASE, __ATOMIC_ACQUIRE));
    return old_val;
}
```

2.4 Quantum-Resistant Security Layer

Cryptographic Suite:

· Key Exchange: CRYSTALS-Kyber-1024 (NIST Post-Quantum Standard)
· Digital Signatures: CRYSTALS-Dilithium5 or Falcon-1024
· Encryption: AES-256-GCM with 256-bit keys
· Hash Functions: SHA3-512, BLAKE2b-512
· Key Derivation: HKDF-SHA512 with context separation

Quantum Key Distribution (QKD):

```
BB84 Protocol Implementation:
1. Alice generates random bits and random bases (+ or ×)
2. Alice sends quantum states (photon polarization) to Bob
3. Bob measures in random bases
4. Alice and Bob compare bases over classical channel
5. They keep bits where bases matched (sifting)
6. Error correction and privacy amplification
7. Shared secret established with information-theoretic security
```

Security Parameters:

· Post-Quantum Security Level: 5 (256-bit classical, 128-bit quantum)
· Key Refresh Interval: 24 hours or 2^48 encryptions
· Forward Secrecy: Ephemeral keys for each session
· Backward Secrecy: Key erasure after session termination

2.5 Distributed Computing Framework

Architecture:

· Master-Worker Pattern: Central scheduler with distributed workers
· Data Parallelism: Split datasets across multiple nodes
· Model Parallelism: Split neural networks across nodes
· Pipeline Parallelism: Sequential stages on different nodes

Communication Patterns:

```
All-Reduce:   O(log P) complexity for P processors
Scatter-Gather: Hierarchical aggregation
Bulk Synchronous Parallel (BSP): Supersteps with barrier synchronization
```

Performance Model:

```
Amdahl's Law: S = 1 / ((1 - p) + p/s)
Where:
S = Speedup
p = Parallelizable fraction
s = Number of processors

Gustafson's Law: S = s + (1 - s) * p
Where s = serial fraction
```

2.6 AI/ML Engine

Ensemble Architecture:

1. LSTM Networks: For temporal sequence prediction
2. Autoencoders: For anomaly detection via reconstruction error
3. Gradient Boosting Machines: For feature importance analysis
4. One-Class SVM: For novelty detection
5. Bayesian Neural Networks: For uncertainty quantification

Training Pipeline:

```
Data Collection → Preprocessing → Feature Engineering → 
Model Training → Hyperparameter Optimization → 
Model Validation → Deployment → Continuous Learning
```

Performance Metrics:

· Accuracy: >99.9% for anomaly detection
· Precision: >99.5% (low false positive rate)
· Recall: >99.7% (low false negative rate)
· F1 Score: >0.995
· Inference Latency: <100ms for real-time applications

